Assume i and j are small integers. Which of the following code snippets swaps i and j without third variable? (^ is a XOR operation bitwise).
A: i=i+j; j=i-j; i=i-j;
B: i=i*j; j=i/j; i=i/j;
C: i=i^j; j=i^j; i=i^j;

Consider the following structure for creating nodes of a double linked list.
struct node {
  int data;
  struct node *x1; /* left pointer */
  struct node *y1; /* right pointer */
};
Let us assume P be the node in the existing linked list. Which of the following is true about the following code C1?
Code C1:
(P→x1)→y1 = P→y1;
(P→y1)→x1 = P→x1;
Assume memory is made free automatically by the compiler after deletion.

Consider the following function.
int fun(int m, int n) {
  if (n==0) return m;
  else return (m + fun(m, n-1));
}
What is the return value of function fun(18, 28)?

Consider the following C code:
int main() {
  int a=25;
  int b;
  b=++a;
  b=a++;
  b=--a;
  b=a;
  printf("%d", b);
  return 0;
}
Number of tokens in the above C code ________.

We are given two strings: String S of length n and string T of length m for the LCS problem, we have produced the following exponential time recursive program.
LCS(S,n,T,m) {
  if (n==0 || m==0) return 0;
  if (S[n]==T[m]) result = 1+LCS(S,n-1,T,m-1);
  else result = max(LCS(S,n-1,T,m), LCS(S,n,T,m-1));
  return result;
}
Then the number of times that LCS(S,1,T,1) is recursively called equals ________.

Consider a relation R(A,B,C,D) and two sets of functional dependencies F1 and F2:
F1 = {CA→B, BA→D, B→D, DB→C}
F2 = {A→B, B→A, AB→C, AC→D, B→C}
Which of the following is true?

Consider the following function.
int BSR(int arr[], int k) {
  int value=0, i, last;
  for (i=0; i<k; i++)
    value += arr[i];
  last = (k*(k-1))/2;
  return (value - last);
}
Assume that the array contains list of all the numbers from 1 to k-1. What is the return value of function BSR?

Consider the following code segment:
struct node {
  struct node *left;
  int data;
  struct node *right;
};
struct node *fun(struct node *P) {
  if (P→right→right == NULL)
    P→right = P→right→left;
  else
    P = fun(P→right);
  return (P);
}
What does the function fun do if root of a binary search tree is passed to the function? Assume left subtree and right subtree of Binary search tree is not NULL.
